<div id="review_3874431265" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3874431265" />
    <a title="Michelle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/127815147-michelle"><img alt="Michelle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1628455046p2/127815147.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3874431265?book_show_action=true">Jan 28, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle" href="/user/show/127815147-michelle">Michelle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3874431265" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1242413272240742509"><i> “Never make your home in a place,” the old man had said, too lazy in the spring warmth to do more than wag a finger. “Make a home for yourself inside your own head. You’ll find what you need to furnish it – memory, friends you can trust, love of learning, and other such things.” Morgenes had grinned. “That way it will go with you wherever you journey. You’ll never lack for a home – unless you lose your head, of course…” </i><br/><br/>The Dragonbone Chair, packed with adventure and life-like characters, wraps</span>
  <span id="freeText1242413272240742509" style="display:none"><i> “Never make your home in a place,” the old man had said, too lazy in the spring warmth to do more than wag a finger. “Make a home for yourself inside your own head. You’ll find what you need to furnish it – memory, friends you can trust, love of learning, and other such things.” Morgenes had grinned. “That way it will go with you wherever you journey. You’ll never lack for a home – unless you lose your head, of course…” </i><br /><br />The Dragonbone Chair, packed with adventure and life-like characters, wraps the reader in a comfort that only original, great fantasy writing can do. While it gives those nostalgic feelings, it also creates a unique experience full of emotion, wit, action, and intrigue. Tad Williams’ methodical pacing is not one that unfurls at break-neck speed, but one that carefully crafts with the feel of relevant foreshadowing and well-balanced building of the characters and setting. I can see how some might call it a bit of a “slow burn,” but it had me engaged the entire time and the dream sequences and descriptions never felt like they needlessly detracted from the storyline. Binabik and Qantaqa clinched this as a five-star read for me and I am eager to see how this series continues. <br /><br /><i> “There is no such thing as ‘fearless,’ Simon – not unless a man is mad. People who are called fearless are usually just good at hiding it, and that is quite a different thing.” </i><br /><br /><i> “Nothing is without cost. There is a price to all power, and it is not always obvious.” </i> <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1242413272240742509" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

