    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3625646517" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3625646517" />
    <a title="Brent" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/93269998-brent"><img alt="Brent" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599143286p2/93269998.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3625646517?book_show_action=true">Jan 07, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brent" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brent" href="/user/show/93269998-brent">Brent</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/93269998-brent?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/93269998-brent?shelf=epic-fantasy">epic-fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/93269998-brent?shelf=osten-ard">osten-ard</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3625646517" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17496504215289369153">I have had all 3 books of Memory Sorry and Thorn on my shelves for over a year, and I&apos;ve just been waiting for the right time to pick them up. Finally with Mike from Mike&apos;s Book Reviews doing a readalong it seemed like the perfect time. My only regret was not getting to these books sooner because I think The Dragonbone Chair was one of my favorite fantasy books I&apos;ve read in a long time.<br/><br/>Over the last few months I&apos;ve caught up on a lot of big series, but MST is one I&apos;ve been sleeping on despite it</span>
  <span id="freeText17496504215289369153" style="display:none">I have had all 3 books of Memory Sorry and Thorn on my shelves for over a year, and I've just been waiting for the right time to pick them up. Finally with Mike from Mike's Book Reviews doing a readalong it seemed like the perfect time. My only regret was not getting to these books sooner because I think The Dragonbone Chair was one of my favorite fantasy books I've read in a long time.<br /><br />Over the last few months I've caught up on a lot of big series, but MST is one I've been sleeping on despite it being a bedrock and inspiration for a lot of the modern fantasy that came after. Pretty much from the instant I picked up The Dragonbone Chair it felt like a breath of fresh air. I've been reading so much grimdark lately I really needed this change of pace that is the type of story that bridges the gap between classic and modern fantasy. It doesn't feel like a fantasy book written in 1988. Honestly it feels like more of a modern fantasy book than something written a couple years later like Eye of The World. This made for a much more enjoyable reading experience for me as the tropes were there, but there was a lot that was unique going on as well. It wasn't so deliberately Tolkien derivative, and in fact you can spot how it influenced later works like A Song of Ice and Fire.<br /><br />I was hooked by the characters and story in this book pretty much from page one, but one thing I really appreciated is how the development of both built and built and really crescendo-ed in part III where it became an absolutely incredible read. Tad does slowly introduce the story in part 1 which seems to be where a lot of modern readers struggle with the pacing, but to me it just felt like an appropriate establishment of the world and characters. I never once felt bored. As things are revealed over the course of the book you become engrossed in the politics, the factions, the mysteries, and what becomes of our characters because we spent time establishing the base early on. By the time we get to the climax in part 3 I did not want to put this book down. Oh and of course I didn't even mention the writing here which is a beautifully descriptive type of prose that I absolutely love to read.<br /><br />As far as what didn't work for me there wasn't much. I think maybe the factions and the politics could be slightly hard to follow at times, but once I realize the real-world cultures they were based on and the naming conventions it became easier. Also, we get enough of it over the course of then novel that it was easier to track by the end.<br /><br />This may end up making my all-time top series list if the following books are as strong as this one. I can't wait to continue.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17496504215289369153" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


