    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2015609074" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2015609074" />
    <a title="Trent" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19885276-trent"><img alt="Trent" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1628888028p2/19885276.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2015609074?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trent" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trent" href="/user/show/19885276-trent">Trent</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/19885276-trent?shelf=osten-ard">osten-ard</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2015609074" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16021669658264832966">I adore this book and series (and the new books set in Osten Ard as well!) Tad Williams has penned an all-time classic. In fact, it is the inspiration for many well-known Fantasy writers: GRRM, Sanderson, Rothfuss, Paolini and others. <br/><br/>This first book is not perfect, however, and so I do want to break a few things down so readers can have an idea of what they are getting into. <br/><br/>So here are a few Pro&apos;s and Con&apos;s of The Dragonbone Chair:<br/><br/>Con&apos;s:<br/><br/>- The beginning of the book is slow, and then even after </span>
  <span id="freeText16021669658264832966" style="display:none">I adore this book and series (and the new books set in Osten Ard as well!) Tad Williams has penned an all-time classic. In fact, it is the inspiration for many well-known Fantasy writers: GRRM, Sanderson, Rothfuss, Paolini and others. <br /><br />This first book is not perfect, however, and so I do want to break a few things down so readers can have an idea of what they are getting into. <br /><br />So here are a few Pro's and Con's of The Dragonbone Chair:<br /><br />Con's:<br /><br />- The beginning of the book is slow, and then even after it begins to 'pick up', there are still pacing issues. I wasn't overly bothered by it, but I can definitely see how it could be a barrier to some readers. It's hard for me to think of too many other books I have read (other than maybe some by Robin Hobb) that have started this slowly - though still confidently.<br /><br />- The world-building is large and complex. There are a lot of names in this book, and they don't always click super easily. It took me a while (and frankly, I'm still not totally clear) to get my head around some of these names, places, and history. I would have loved for there to be a solid Wiki like you find for ASOIAF, Malazan, WoT, etc.<br /><br />Now let's talk about the Pro's:<br /><br />- PROSE! (See what I did there?) But seriously, the writing. My god, the writing. I feel like I've never really heard /read anyone discuss Tad William's prose before, but he deserve to be in the same category as Hobb, Rothfuss, GGK, and the other wordsmiths in Fantasy. His skill is honestly what kept me going, even when the pacing was a bit too slow. Just an absolute joy to read, while still being totally approachable for readers of all ages.<br /><br />- The characters also stand out, particularly Simon. I can see why some readers might be annoyed by him, but I really grew to love him - even more than comparable characters like FitzChivalry Farseer or Kvothe. I loved how fallible he was, but also how he perseveres and grows. He's so earnest that's it's impossible *not* to love him, IMO. I enjoyed many of the side characters as well - Marya, Binabak, Josua, etc. <br /><br />- The lore, while confusing at times, was still very well thought out and had me yearning to learn more. I love that it feels almost like it's ripped out of our history - there are even hints of a Christianity-like religion. It just feels like there is a lot more to be learned below the surface, which I really love.<br /><br />Overall, this was a great read - particularly when you look at in the context of when it came out, preceding Wheel of Time, ASOIAF, Realm of the Elderlings, and other modern Fantasy giants. It feels almost like the beginning of modern Fantasy, in many ways. Definitely worth your time, and highly recommended. I can't wait to start The Stone of Farewell!</span>
  <a data-text-id="16021669658264832966" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


